.TH BCR 8 "2026-06-27" "bcr 0.2.0" "System Administration"
.SH NAME
bcr \- broadcast relay for Linux
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B bcr
.B \-i
.I iface
.RB [ \-i
.IR iface ...]
.B \-o
.I iface
.RB [ \-o
.IR iface ...]
.RB [ \-c
.IR file ]
.RB [ \-u
.IR user ]
.RB [ \-\-no\-drop ]
.RB [ \-\-rate\-limit
.IR pps ]
.RB [ \-\-rate\-burst
.IR n ]
.RB [ \-v ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B bcr
relays IPv4 UDP broadcast and multicast packets between network interfaces using
.B AF_PACKET
sockets. It is a hardened, modernized replacement for
.BR bcrelay (8)
from the pptpd project.
.PP
Each input interface is captured through an
.B AF_PACKET / SOCK_DGRAM
socket carrying a kernel BPF filter that passes only IPv4 UDP frames destined to
a multicast or broadcast address. For every such packet,
.B bcr
validates the headers, matches it against the configured rules (first match
wins; deny by default), optionally rate-limits it, and forwards it out every
.I other
output interface \(em never back out the interface it arrived on. The
destination is rewritten to the output interface's broadcast address (multicast
destinations are preserved), checksums are recomputed, and a loop-prevention
marker is applied.
.PP
.B bcr
must be started as root (or with
.BR CAP_NET_RAW )
to create the raw sockets. By default it then drops to an unprivileged user;
see
.BR "PRIVILEGES" .
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-i ", " \-\-input " iface"
Interface to receive broadcasts from. Required. May be given more than once to
capture on several interfaces.
.TP
.BI \-o ", " \-\-output " iface"
Interface to relay broadcasts to. Required. May be given more than once. An
interface listed as both input and output participates in a bidirectional relay;
a packet is never echoed back out its ingress interface.
.TP
.BI \-c ", " \-\-config " file"
Path to the configuration file (see
.BR "CONFIGURATION FILE" ).
.B This option has no default.
There is
.I no
implicit
.I /etc/bcr.conf
and no other default path. If
.B \-c
is omitted,
.B bcr
runs with a built-in allow-all rule and relays
.I every
captured broadcast and multicast packet. To get filtered, deny-by-default
behavior you must pass
.B \-c
explicitly. The packaged
.BR systemd (1)
unit always passes
.BR "\-c /etc/bcr.conf" .
.TP
.BI \-u ", " \-\-user " user"
User to drop privileges to after the sockets are created. Defaults to
.BR nobody .
See
.BR "PRIVILEGES" .
.TP
.B \-\-no\-drop
Do not drop privileges; run as root for the entire lifetime. Not recommended.
.TP
.BI \-\-rate\-limit " pps"
Maximum packets per second to relay.
.B 0
(the default) means unlimited. Because each accepted packet is fanned out to
every output interface, a limit here caps broadcast-storm amplification.
.TP
.BI \-\-rate\-burst " n"
Token-bucket burst capacity for
.BR \-\-rate\-limit .
Defaults to one second's worth of the configured rate. The bucket holds up to
.I n
tokens and refills at the rate; packets arriving with an empty bucket are
dropped.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-verbose
Also log packets that were filtered or dropped, not just relayed packets.
.SH "CONFIGURATION FILE"
The configuration is a line-based allowlist. Blank lines and lines beginning
with
.B #
are ignored. Each rule has the form:
.PP
.RS
.nf
ACTION PROTO SRC_IP[:SRC_PORT] DST_IP[:DST_PORT] [NAT_OPTIONS]
.fi
.RE
.PP
Rules are evaluated top to bottom and the first match wins. Any packet matching
no rule is denied \(em deny-by-default is built in, so a trailing
.B "deny any any:any any:any"
is unnecessary.
.TP
.B ACTION
.B allow
or
.BR deny .
.TP
.B PROTO
.B udp
or
.BR any .
TCP has no broadcast/multicast semantics and is rejected at parse time.
.TP
.B SRC_IP, DST_IP
A dotted-quad address, a CIDR block
.RI ( x.x.x.x/n ),
or
.BR any .
.B DST_IP
also accepts
.B 255.255.255.255
(limited broadcast),
.B directed
(a subnet-directed broadcast such as 192.168.1.255), and
.BR any .
.TP
.B SRC_PORT, DST_PORT
A single port, an inclusive range
.IR start - end ,
or
.BR any .
.TP
.B NAT_OPTIONS
Optional, and only valid on
.B allow
rules:
.BR snat= IP ,
.BR dnat= IP ,
.BR sport= PORT ,
.BR dport= PORT .
.PP
Parsing is strict:
.B bcr
exits at startup with a line-numbered error rather than silently misbehaving.
An unknown or misspelled option, an invalid address/port/CIDR, an inverted port
range, or NAT options on a
.B deny
rule are all hard errors.
.SH PRIVILEGES
Creating an
.B AF_PACKET
socket requires
.B CAP_NET_RAW
(root).
.B bcr
opens its sockets first and then, unless
.B \-\-no\-drop
is given, drops privileges to the account named by
.B \-u
(default
.BR nobody ):
it sets the supplementary groups, gid, and uid of that account and then verifies
it can no longer regain root. The relay loop performs only
.BR read (2)
and
.BR sendto (2)
on already-open descriptors, which require no privileges. The user dropped to
is printed at startup; if the drop or the re-escalation check fails,
.B bcr
exits rather than continue as root.
.SH "LOOP PREVENTION"
.B bcr
prevents relay loops two ways. Structurally, it never relays a packet back out
the interface it arrived on. Additionally, relayed packets are marked with
TTL=1 and the IPv4 Identification field set to
.BR 0xBCBC ;
a packet arriving with both is treated as already-relayed and dropped, which
catches loops between separate
.B bcr
instances on a shared segment. Unlike the original bcrelay,
.B bcr
does not zero the UDP checksum as a marker (a zero checksum is legal and
common); it recomputes a valid UDP checksum on every relayed packet.
.SH "EXIT STATUS"
.B bcr
exits non-zero on a configuration error, a missing or down interface,
insufficient privileges, or a failed privilege drop. Once running it stays in
the foreground until killed.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Relay only what \fI/etc/bcr.conf\fR allows, from eth0 to eth1:
.B sudo bcr \-i eth0 \-o eth1 \-c /etc/bcr.conf
.TP
Bidirectional relay between two segments:
.B sudo bcr \-i eth0 \-i eth1 \-o eth0 \-o eth1 \-c /etc/bcr.conf
.TP
Cap a storm at 5000 pps with a 10000-packet burst:
.B sudo bcr \-i eth0 \-o eth1 \-c /etc/bcr.conf \-\-rate\-limit 5000 \-\-rate\-burst 10000
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/bcr.conf
Conventional configuration file location. It is
.I only
read when passed explicitly with
.BR \-c ;
it is not a built-in default.
.TP
.I /etc/default/bcr
Environment file read by the packaged
.BR systemd (1)
unit, supplying the
.B \-i
/
.B \-o
interface flags and any extra options.
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.BR bcrelay (8),
.BR systemd (1),
.BR tcpdump (8)
.PP
Original bcrelay: https://sources.debian.org/src/pptpd/
